  "local_port": 33342,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "I'm a rookie. How should I start preparing for getting selected in GSoC 17?",
  "response": "Preparing for Google Summer of Code (GSoC) is an exciting and rewarding journey, especially if you're a beginner. Here\u2019s a step-by-step guide to help you get started and increase your chances of being selected for **GSoC 2024** (assuming you meant the latest edition):\n\n---\n\n### 1. **Understand GSoC**\n   - **What is GSoC?**  \n     GSoC is a global program where students contribute to open-source projects under the guidance of mentors. You get paid for your contributions.\n   - **Eligibility**:  \n     Check the eligibility criteria on the [GSoC website](https://summerofcode.withgoogle.com/). Typically, you must be 18+ and a student (or recent graduate).\n   - **Timeline**:  \n     Familiarize yourself with the GSoC timeline (e.g., organizations announced, proposal submission, coding period).\n\n---\n\n### 2. **Learn the Basics of Open Source**\n   - **Git and GitHub**:  \n     Learn how to use Git for version control and GitHub for collaborating on projects.\n   - **Open Source Etiquette**:  \n     Understand how open-source communities work: communication, issue tracking, pull requests, code reviews, etc.\n\n---\n\n### 3. **Choose a Programming Language**\n   - Pick a language you\u2019re comfortable with or willing to learn. Popular languages in GSoC include Python, C++, Java, JavaScript, and Go.\n   - Build small projects to solidify your skills.\n\n---\n\n### 4. **Explore GSoC Organizations**\n   - Visit the [GSoC website](https://summerofcode.withgoogle.com/) and check the list of participating organizations from previous years.\n   - Look for organizations that align with your interests and skills.\n   - Start exploring their projects, codebase, and issue trackers.\n\n---\n\n### 5. **Get Involved Early**\n   - **Join Communities**:  \n     Join mailing lists, Discord/Slack channels, or IRC chats of the organizations you\u2019re interested in.\n   - **Start Contributing**:  \n     Look for \u201cgood first issues\u201d or beginner-friendly tasks. Contribute code, documentation, or bug fixes.\n   - **Build Relationships**:  \n     Interact with mentors and community members. Show genuine interest in their projects.\n\n---\n\n### 6. **Prepare a Strong Proposal**\n   - Research the project ideas listed by organizations or suggest your own if allowed.\n   - Break down the project into clear, achievable milestones.\n   - Include details about your skills, relevant experience, and timeline.\n   - Get feedback from mentors or peers before submitting.\n\n---\n\n### 7. **Build a Portfolio**\n   - Work on personal projects or contribute to other open-source projects to showcase your skills.\n   - Maintain an active GitHub profile with clean, well-documented code.\n\n---\n\n### 8. **Stay Consistent**\n   - Open-source contributions require time and effort. Stay consistent and keep improving.\n   - Be proactive in seeking help and learning from your contributions.\n\n---\n\n### 9. **Prepare for the Selection Process**\n   - Practice solving coding challenges (e.g., LeetCode, HackerRank) to prepare for technical interviews or tests.\n   - Be ready to explain your contributions and proposal in detail.\n\n---\n\n### 10. **Stay Updated**\n   - Follow the [GSoC blog](https://opensource.googleblog.com/) and official social media channels for updates.\n   - Join communities like Reddit (r/GSoC) or Discord servers for tips and support.\n\n---\n\n### Resources to Get Started\n   - [Git Handbook](https://guides.github.com/introduction/git-handbook/)\n   - [First Contributions](https://github.com/firstcontributions/first-contributions)\n   - [GSoC Student Guide](https://google.github.io/gsocguides/student/)\n   - [Open Source Guides](https://opensource.guide/)\n\n---\n\n### Key Tips\n   - Start early! The more time you spend contributing and building relationships, the better your chances.\n   - Be patient and persistent. Open source can be challenging, but it\u2019s a great learning experience.\n   - Focus on quality over quantity in your contributions.\n\nGood luck with your GSoC journey! Let me know if you need more specific guidance. \ud83d\ude0a",
  "temperature": 1.0,
